<H1>Fusion</H1>
<P class=3DMsoNormal>A potentially fusible speaker detector is one that =
takes=20
speech, <I>x</I>, as input and which outputs a real scalar =91score=92 =
<I>s(x)</I>.=20
A <I>fusion</I> of <I>N</I> such detectors is also a function from =
<I>x</I> to a=20
fused score, namely=20
<I>s<SUB>fused</SUB>(x)&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;f(s<SUB>1</SUB>(x),s<SUB>2</SUB>(x)=
,</I><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol; mso-ascii-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; =
mso-hansi-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-char-type: symbol; =
mso-symbol-font-family: Symbol"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-char-type: symbol; mso-symbol-font-family: =
Symbol">=BC</SPAN></SPAN>,s<SUB>N</SUB>(x))</I>.</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><![if =
!supportEmptyParas]><![endif]>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal>There are many different forms that the function =
<I>f</I> can=20
take. In cases where the function is dependent on parameters, these =
parameters=20
can be trained on some development data. We give MATLAB code for two =
examples of=20
simple linear fusion. These differ in the objective function that is =
used to=20
train the fusion parameters:</P>
